@using MC.MvcQuickNav
@(DependencyResolver.Current.GetService<string>())

<blockquote>A series of ASP.NET MVC HTML helpers designed to render common navigation controls with the minimum of fuss.
    <br />
    You're looking at them right now!
</blockquote>

<h3>What's Included</h3>

@{ Html.RenderPartial("_Controls"); }

<h3>Features</h3>

<ul>
    <li>All navigation controls are generated from a single XML sitemap file.
        <ul>
            <li>Don't want to use an XML file? You can write 
                @Html.ActionLink("your own provider", "inavigationtreeprovider", "controls").</li>
        </ul> 
    </li>
    <li>The controls generate clean, standard, semantic markup, 
        (only <code>ul</code>, <code>li</code>, <code>a</code>, <code>span</code> tags) making them easy to style.</li>
    <li>Support an arbitrary depth of navigation (though make sure your CSS can cope with it!).</li>
    <li>Supports tooltips and opening in a new window.</li>
    <li>Tracks user's current node automatically from the URL.
        <ul>
            <li>An <code>active</code> CSS class is added to this node, which allows the current node to be distinguished using CSS.</li>
            <li>Calculated by finding the node with the closest matching URL to the user's current URL.
                Does not use controller names or actions, giving total flexibility.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Backwards compatible with ASP.NET Webform's sitemap file format.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Quick Start</h3>

<ol>
    <li>Add a reference to the library, either from the NuGet package or by downloading from GitHub:
        <ul>
            <li><code>Install-Package MC.MvcQuickNav</code></li>
            <li><a href="https://github.com/chambem9/MC.MvcQuickNav">Download the source from GitHub</a> (including this example website)</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Create a sitemap file called web.sitemap in the root of your website:
        <ul>
            <li><a href="https://gist.github.com/chambem9/4983670/raw/67226db1a1a18a9966c4378318604174df94a7c5/sitemap.xml">Example web.sitemap</a></li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>In your view, add a using directive and call a helper to automatically render a navigation control from your sitemap:
        <ul>
            <li><code>@@using MC.MvcQuickNav</code></li>
            <li><code>@@Html.NavigationMenu()</code></li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Apply CSS styles to make your control look beautiful:
        <ul>
            <li><a href="https://gist.github.com/chambem9/4984751/raw/5bc22e45e6b3025865ac9c9b92844b40ac0b86e3/example-menu.css">Example CSS file for the navigation menu</a></li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ol>

<blockquote>@Html.ActionLink("Check out the walkthrough for more details", "walkthrough", "home")</blockquote>

